</ref> [[Amiga]], [[Commodore 64]], [[Apple II series|Apple II]], [[Macintosh]], and [[DOS]] was produced.{{Citation needed|date=October 2015}} Interstel warned customers "Don't buy Empire! It is a Krellan plot to reduce productivity".<ref name="cgw198711">{{cite magazine | title=Christmas Buyers Guide | magazine=[[Computer Gaming World]] | date=November 1987 | page=24 | url=https://archive.org/details/Computer_Gaming_World_Issue_41/page/n23 | issue=41}}</ref>

==Reception==
''[[Computer Gaming World]]'' stated that ''Empire'' was "a fascinating grand strategic wargame, more sophisticated than [[Risk (game)|Risk]], but easier to play than [[Rise and Decline of the Third Reich|Third Reich]]".<ref name="cgw198711"/> The magazine's full review noted the improved [[user interface|UI]], saying "the playability of an already successful system has been significantly enhanced".<ref name="CGW">{{Cite news |url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1988&pub=2&id=43 |title=Empire: The Rise and Fall of Random Empires |last=Kritzen |first=William |date=January 1988 |magazine=[[Computer Gaming World]] |pages=40–42}}</ref> The game would later receive the magazine's "Game of the Year" award for 1988;<ref name = "CGWaward">{{Cite news | date = October 1988 | magazine = [[Computer Gaming World]] | title = Computer Gaming World's 1988 Game of the Year Awards | page = 54 | url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1988&pub=2&id=52}}</ref> in 1989 the magazine named ''Empire'' to its Hall of Fame for games readers rated highly over time, with a final score of 9.71 out of 12,<ref name="cgw198905">{{cite news | title=Game Rating Chart | magazine=Computer Gaming World | date=May 1989 | url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1989&pub=2&id=59 | accessdate=3 November 2013 | pages=56}}</ref> in 1990 readers voted for the game as their "All-Time Favorite",<ref name="cgw199001">{{cite news | url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1990&pub=2&id=67 | title=CGW Readers Select All-Time Favorites | magazine=Computer Gaming World | date=January 1990 | accessdate=15 November 2013 | pages=64}}</ref> a 1991 magazine survey of strategy and war games gave it four and a half stars out of five,<ref name="brooks199111">{{cite news | url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1991&pub=2&id=88 | title=Computer Strategy and Wargames: The 1900-1950 Epoch / Part I (A-L) of an Annotated Paiktography | magazine=Computer Gaming World | date=November 1991 | accessdate=18 November 2013 | author=Brooks, M. Evan | pages=138}}</ref> and a 1993 survey in the magazine gave the game three stars out of five.<ref name="brooks199309">{{cite news | url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1993&pub=2&id=110 | title=Brooks' Book of Wargames: 1900-1950, A-P | magazine=Computer Gaming World | date=September 1993 | accessdate=30 July 2014 | author=Brooks, M. Evan | pages=118}}</ref> ''[[Compute!]]'' agreed with the warning on the game box of its addictiveness, stating that the game combined aspects of exploration and strategy. The magazine also praised the UI, and called the game "superb" and "addictive".<ref name="randall198803">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1988-03-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_094_1988_Mar#page/n27/mode/2up | title=Empire | work=Compute! | date=March 1988 | accessdate=10 November 2013 | author=Randall, Neil | pages=26}}</ref> [[Jerry Pournelle]] of ''[[Byte (magazine)|BYTE]]'' also agreed about its addictiveness. While stating that the UI could be improved, he noted that ''Empire'' avoided the need to micromanage units that made games like ''[[Anacreon: Reconstruction 4021]]'' tedious. Pournelle concluded that ''Empire'' tempts players to play a little longer and find out what is going to happen next.<ref name="pournelle198901">{{Cite magazine |last=Pournelle |first=Jerry |author-link=Jerry Pournelle |date=January 1989 |title=To the Stars |url=https://archive.org/stream/byte-magazine-1989-01/1989_01_BYTE_14-01_PC_Communications_and_Annual_Awards_and_Digitizing_Tablets#page/n137/mode/2up |magazine=BYTE |page=109}}</ref> The [[Atari ST]] version of the game was reviewed in 1988 in ''[[Dragon (magazine)|Dragon]]'' #131 by Hartley, Patricia, and Kirk Lesser in "The Role of Computers" column. The reviewers gave the game 4 out of 5 stars.<ref name="Dragon131">{{cite journal
